ric patient receiving standard doses of trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole." Am J Med Sci 311 (1996): 84-5[26] Marinella MA "Trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole associated with hyperkalemia." West J Med 167 (1997): 356-8[27] Antoniou T, Gomes T, Juurlink DN, Loutfy MR, Glazier RH, Mamdani MM "Trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole-induced hyperkalemia in patients receiving inhibitors of the renin-angiotensin system: a population-based study." Arch Intern Med 170 (2010): 1045-9[28] Hsu I, Wordell CJ "Hyperkalemia and high-dose trimethoprim/sulfamethoxazole." Ann Pharmacother 29 (1995): 427-9[29] Lin SH, Kuo AA, Yu FC, Lin YF "Reversible voltage-dependent distal renal tubular acidosis in a patient receiving standaard doses of trimethoprim-sulphamethoxazole." Nephrol Dial Transplant 12 (1997): 1031-33[30] Lawson DH, O''Connor PC, Jick H "Drug attributed alterations in potassium handling in congestive cardiac failure." Eur J Clin Pharmacol 23 (1982): 21-5[31] Lawson DH "Adverse reactions to potassium chloride." Q J Med 43 (1974): 433-40[32] Perazella MA, Alappan R, Buller GK "Hyperkalemia and trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole." Ann Intern Med 125 (1996): 1015[33] "Product Information. Bactrim (trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole)." Roche Laboratories, Nutley, NJ.[34] Mihm LB, Rathbun RC, Resmantargoff BH "Hyperkalemia associated with high-dose trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole in a patient with the acquired immunodeficiency syndrome." Pharmacotherapy 15 (1995): 793-7[35] Lee SW, Park SW, Kang JM "Intraoperative hyperkalemia induced by administration of trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole in a patient receiving angiotensin receptor blockers." J Clin Anesth 26 (2014): 427-8', 1767369485);
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO drug_interactions (id, ingredient1, ingredient2, severity, effect, arabic_effect, recommendation, arabic_recommendation, management_text, mechanism_text, alternatives_a, alternatives_b, risk_level, ddinter_id, source, type, metabolism_info, source_url, reference_text, updated_at) VALUES (109277, 'Abemaciclib', 'Dalfopristin', 'Moderate', 'Coadministration with inhibitors of CYP450 3A4 may increase the plasma concentrations of abemaciclib and its pharmacologically active metabolites, all of which are substrates of the isoenzyme.', NULL, 'Caution is advised when abemaciclib is used with moderate CYP450 3A4 inhibitors.', NULL, 'Caution is advised when abemaciclib is used with moderate CYP450 3A4 inhibitors. Dosage adjustments for abemaciclib in 50 mg decrements may be necessary and should be done in accordance with the product labeling. Patients should be monitored for potentially increased adverse effects such as nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, stomatitis, venous thromboembolism, hepatotoxicity, anemia, neutropenia, and thrombocytopenia.', 'Metabolism', 'Dabrafenib, Dacomitinib, Vemurafenib, Vandetanib, Afatinib, Tivozanib, Sunitinib, Regorafenib, Alpelisib, Lenvatinib, Erlotinib, More', NULL, 'Moderate', NULL, 'DDInter', 'pharmacodynamic', NULL, 'https://ddinter2.scbdd.com/server/interact/109401/', '[1] "Product Information. Verzenio (abemaciclib)." Lilly, Eli and Company, Indianapolis, IN.[2] "Product Information. Verzenio (abemaciclib)." Lilly, Eli and Company, Indianapolis, IN.', 1767369485);
